Custom Plotting Functions for rtsVis

Johannes Mast

2020-11-21

Introduction

In rtsVis, graphs are created using the rtsVis::ts_flow_frames() function. This function takes as inputs a list of raster objects r_list (usually preprocessed with rtsVis::ts_raster() ) as well as a number of positions which can be point or polygon objects of sf or sp. It extracts the raster values intersecting these objects and passes the extracted dataframe extract_df to a plotting function, along with a sequence of values val_seq which contain plausible values for interval breaks of the values. For every frame, the plotting function is applied to create a ggplot2 object. The output of rtsVis::ts_flow_frames() is therefore a list of ggplot2 objects of equal length as the input r_list.

Types of plots

Spatial Scope

Depending on the type of input geometries, the plots that can plausibly be created can differ.

When using points, the extracted extract_df will contain one value per frame and position. This is suitable for plotting of trends and amounts, such as in:

  • Scatterplots
  • Line Charts
  • Bar Charts

When using points with a buffer or polygons as positions, the extracted extract_df will usually contain more than one value per frame and position.

This enables plotting of distributions or proportions, for example via:

  • Violin Plots
  • Histograms
  • Pie Charts

We may also be interested in plotting summary statistics for the positions. In this case, we can within apply a summary function such as mean or var within our custom plotting function. We can also pass the FUN directly to rtsVis::ts_flow_frames() via the FUN parameter, in which case it will be applied during extraction. The statistics can then be plotted in similar ways as the singular values extracted from points.

Temporal Scope

For some type of plots, we want each frame to provide a snapshot of the data at a certain point in time, without regard for the context the time series provides. This is the case for the violin plot type implemented in rtsVis:

Violin Frames

The temporal dimension can later be brought back in via animation. But every individual frame visualises only one point in time. Contrast that with the line plot type:

Line Frames

In this type, we visualise not only the value at the current point in time but also all previous values.

Other plot types are conceivable which might visualise future values or points within a time window around the current frame.

Custom Plotting Functions

Requirements

Writing a custom plotting function is no more complicated than writing a ggplot. In fact, a ggplot will usually form the main body of such a function. For compatibility with rtsVis::ts_flow_frames() we must also consider that it should:

  • usually subset the extracted tibble dataframe to be in line with the temporal scope
  • return a ggplot object
  • accept (and optionally, but ideally also implement) the following arguments, which are prepared by ts_flow_frames:
    • i: The index of the current frame. This is used to grab the data which is relevant for the current frame from edf
    • edf: The extracted tibble containing values for plotting. The format of this tibble will be discussed in detail in the following section.
    • pl: Position legend. A logical value that indicates whether a legend for the positions should be plotted. Only useful if abp that is, if any aesthetic is mapped to position.
    • bl: Band legend. A logical value that indicates whether a legend for the bands should be plotted.
    • plt: Position legend title.
    • blt: Band legend title.
    • lp: Legend position.
    • ps: Plot size. This should be passed to a ggplot geom. As it is treated differently depending on the type of geom, it should sometimes be adjusted by a factor.
    • vs: Value sequence. A sequence of values like c(0,1250,2500,3750,5000). This is calculated across all extracted values and allows the user to pass breaks in a value scale.
    • abp: Aesthetics by position? A logical value that indicates whether some aesthetic should be mapped to the position. For example, every point could be represented by a different linetype in a line plot.

The plotting function may or may not use any of these arguments. We recommend to implement as many of them as possible, for consistency with other functions.

The plotting function may also take any number of additional arguments, which can be passed via ellipsis (...) when calling rtsVis::ts_flow_frames().

Input Data Format

As described previously, the plotting function will receive data in the form of a [tibble]{https://tibble.tidyverse.org/} dataframe. It is in long format, with each row corresponding to a combination of band, position and frame:

  • position_name: Character, a position name either passed bei the user or generically generated byrtsVis::ts_flow_frames()
  • centr_lon: Numeric, the longitude of the centroid of the position.
  • centr_lat: Numeric, the latitude of the centroid of the position.
  • time: Date, the date of the frame.
  • frame: Numeric, the number of the current frame. This can be used in conjunction with i (see previous section) to select the relevant rows from the tibble.
  • band: Character, a band name either passed by the user or generically generated by rtsVis::ts_flow_frames()
  • value: Numeric or Integer, the extracted value for this band, position, and frame.
  • band_colors: Character, a color either passed by the user or generically generated by rtsVis::ts_flow_frames()

Example

Below, we create a plotting function that creates a barchart.

library(ggplot2)
barplot <- function(i, edf , pl,lp, bl, blt,plt, ps, vs,abp,plot_title){
  #The data up to the current frame (this will be plotted)
  x = edf[edf$frame == i,]    
  #All data (this sets the frame)
  y=edf
  
  ## generate base plot
  p <- ggplot(x, aes(x = band,y=value,fill=band))
  ## style it
  p <- p +
    geom_bar(stat = "identity")+
    theme_bw() + 
    theme(aspect.ratio = 1) +
    scale_y_continuous( breaks = vs,limits = c(min(vs),max(vs)))+
    theme(legend.position = lp)+
    facet_grid(~position_name)+
    scale_x_discrete(guide = guide_axis(n.dodge = 2))
  #add the colors
  p <- p +
    scale_fill_manual(values = x$band_colors,breaks = x$band, name=blt)
  
  if(!is.null(plot_title)){
    p <- p+
      ggtitle(label = plot_title)
  }
  
  return(p)
}
library(sf)
library(rtsVis)
# Read required data
r_list_filled_interpolated <- readRDS("Beispieldaten/MODIS/WesternCape/MODIS_WesternCape_filled_interpolated.rds")
points <- st_read("Beispieldaten/Ancillary/WesternCape/Western_Cape_pts.shp")
points <- st_transform(points, crs = st_crs(r_list_filled_interpolated[[1]]))
#Create the frames
bar_frames <- rtsVis::ts_flow_frames(r_list = r_list_filled_interpolated,
                                      positions = points[c(1,3,4),],
                                      plot_function = barplot,
                                      position_names = points$pointname[c(1,3,4)],
                                      band_names = c("620 - 670","841 - 876","459 - 479","545 - 565"),
                                      band_colors = c("firebrick3","darkorchid3","dodgerblue3","olivedrab3"),
                                      band_legend_title = "Wavelength [nm]",
                                      position_legend = T,
                                      legend_position = "left",
                                      band_legend=T,
                                      aes_by_pos = T,
                                      plot_title="Amazing Plot")
# Examine one of the frames
bar_frames[[50]]

We can animate this barchart like any other: Using functionality provided by moveVis: animate_frames()

 moveVis::animate_frames(bar_frames,out_file = "../Beispielbilder/barplot_anim.gif")

Getting Started

Example Inputs

The two code chunks below provide examples for typical arguments which the plot function might receive from rtsVis::ts_flow_frames(). Among them are two examples for extract_df tibbles you can download from the associated repo.

You can define your own plotting function and then apply it to the extract_df to create flow_frames.

Firstly, a typical environment using values extracted from points.

# Setup for points

#Downloading an example tibble containing data extracted from points

download.file("https://github.com/JohMast/rtsVis_demo/raw/main/example__point.rds","extract_df_example_point.rds")

extract_df <- readRDS("extract_df_example_point.rds")[[1]]
val_seq <- readRDS("extract_df_example_point.rds")[[2]]

band_legend_title = "Wavelength [nm]"
band_legend=F
position_legend=T
position_legend_title="POIs"
legend_position="left"
path_size=1
aes_by_pos=T

plot_function <-  #<<<<<<<<Your new plotting function goes here

#Create the frames using your new plotting function
flow_frames <- lapply(1:max(extract_df$frame), function(i){
  plot_function(i=i,
                edf = extract_df,
                bl = band_legend,
                pl = position_legend,
                lp = legend_position,
                blt = band_legend_title,
                plt = position_legend_title,
                ps = plot_size,
                vs = val_seq,
                abp = aes_by_pos#,
                #Any other arguments we might have
                # In the actual ts_flow_frames, those can be passed by ellipsis ...
                #...
                )
})


#Examine one frame
flow_frames[[50]]

Secondly, you could also use values extracted from polygons (as in the default violin plot):
